Sure, Oscar nominations can give any individual movie a boost=E2=80=94e.g.,=
 last year=E2=80=99s =E2=80=98The Zone of Interest=E2=80=99=E2=80=94but unl=
ess a big mainstream hit is catching a lucrative second wind, the post-noms=
 war is largely waged on streaming platforms.

Scott Mendelson ( https://puck.news/author/scott-mendelson/?utm_campaign=3D=
What+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F27%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m=
+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F27%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Scott Mendelson ( https://puck.news/author/scott-mendelson/?utm_campaign=3D=
What+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F27%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m=
+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F27%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

In the old days, Oscar season used to feature one or two
mainstream films that would score a handful of nominations, expand into wid=
e release, and do big numbers. American Hustle, The Revenant, and Hidden Fi=
gures, for instance, all ultimately landed in $155 million to $185 million =
territory. This past weekend, however, just days after the nominations for =
the 97th Academy Awards were announced, the box office was objectively meh,=
 totaling just $66 million in domestic revenue.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Part of the explanation is that this year=E2=80=99s holiday holdovers aren=
=E2=80=99t as big as a Star Wars or an Avatar, but there=E2=80=99s also a c=
onspicuous absence of an Oscar contender with broad appeal. The earnings fr=
om those mainstream winners are the difference between pre- and post-Covid =
box office, when big movies=E2=80=94ones that didn=E2=80=99t need awards at=
tention to succeed=E2=80=94pulled down a handful of nominations to push the=
m over the top and boost total gross
during the first months of the year.

=C2=A0

Indeed, this weekend=E2=80=99s box office is down 46 percent from the same =
period in 2020, which was also the last time one of those bigger movies got=
 an awards season boost: Sam Mendes=E2=80=99 World War I thriller 1917 race=
d to $159 million in North America and $384 million worldwide on a $95 mill=
ion budget. That year=E2=80=99s eventual best picture winner,
Parasite, earned $53 million in North America, a near-record domestic amoun=
t for a non-English-language feature, and $262 million worldwide. Just one =
year earlier, best picture winner Green Book earned more than $320 million =
worldwide, including $71 million in China.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The closest thing we=E2=80=99ve had to a mainstream Oscar season breakout h=
it since the beginning of the Covid
pandemic was Yorgos Lanthimos=E2=80=99s Poor Things, which earned $111 mill=
ion worldwide in late 2023 and early 2024 and won Emma Stone her second Osc=
ar for best actress. This season, judging by the first post-noms weekend, t=
he only two Oscar bump beneficiaries are Searchlight=E2=80=99s A Complete U=
nknown, the Bob Dylan biopic starring Timoth=C3=A9e Chalamet, and A24=E2=80=
=99s epic The Brutalist, starring Adrien
Brody. A Complete Unknown lost 490 theaters after playing in 2,500 over the=
 M.L.K. weekend, but box office fell just 17 percent, for a $3.1 million fi=
fth weekend and $63 million domestic so far. Meanwhile, The Brutalist added=
 780 theaters for a total of 1,118, and earned $2.8 million (+46 percent we=
ek over week), bringing its domestic total to $9.33 million.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

More modest Oscar nomination
bumps included Paramount=E2=80=99s September 5, which was snubbed for best =
picture but earned $770,000 (+120 percent) in 394 theaters, while surprise =
best picture nominee I=E2=80=99m Still Here earned $240,000 (+117 percent) =
in 17 theaters. A Real Pain added $76,000 (+27 percent) in 180 theaters, bu=
t it=E2=80=99s already available on V.O.D. and Hulu, diluting the nominatio=
n benefits. If studios are releasing a potential mainstream contender like =
Conclave or last season=E2=80=99s
The Holdovers partially to capitalize on potential Oscar recognition, havin=
g those films on the same short theatrical-to-V.O.D. pipeline can be self-d=
efeating.=C2=A0

A New
Paradigm
--------

Of course, shorter theatrical windows generally do not clip the
wings of successful releases. But it=E2=80=99s no coincidence that the two =
main beneficiaries this season (at least after one weekend) are still exclu=
sive to theaters. Buzzy sleepers Anora and Conclave boast 14 Oscar noms bet=
ween them, but they were released earlier in the fall and have been availab=
le at home for months. As IndieWire=E2=80=99s Tom Brueggemann
noted ( https://www.indiewire.com/news/box-office/post-oscar-nominations-aw=
ards-hopefuls-thrive-at-home-1235088929/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+=
-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F27%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%281%2F27%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&ut=
m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on Monday, the films participating in this ye=
ar=E2=80=99s Oscar competition are well-represented amid the various V.O.D.=
 platforms, such as Fandango at Home and iTunes.

=C2=A0

Amusingly, one major contender that hasn=E2=80=99t received much of a bump =
is Emilia
P=C3=A9rez: The musical, which netted the most noms of any film with 13, ha=
s grossed only $11 million worldwide, and it has been M.I.A. on the Netflix=
 top 10 domestic viewership chart since its mid-November streaming launch. =
(Netflix has the film only in North America and the U.K.) The awards season=
 is being redefined as an inevitably gloomy part of early winter, when movi=
egoers catch up on nominated films via V.O.D. platforms and streamers. Stud=
ios might not mind this, but theaters surely
do.=C2=A0

