The decline in awards season box office is partially about
shifting audiences habits, and what=E2=80=99s now considered theater-worthy=
=E2=80=94whether audiences will leave the house even to see a Steven Spielb=
erg=E2=80=93directed musical or a Will Smith=E2=80=93starring sports biopic=
 that they=E2=80=99ll be able to watch at home in a month or two. In fact, =
any number of the previous decade=E2=80=99s Oscar season breakouts=E2=80=94=
Slumdog Millionaire, The King=E2=80=99s Speech, Silver Linings Playbook, or=
 La La Land=E2=80=94would probably struggle
theatrically today.

=C2=A0

The notion of mainstream Oscar contenders like A Beautiful Mind, Black Swan=
, or The Shape of Water platforming as early as October or as late as Decem=
ber and then expanding to blockbuster-sized business in January also may be=
 a relic of the recent past. But there=E2=80=99s still something to be said=
 for releasing films late in the year and chasing awards season glory.
Say what you will about the Oscars, but Hollywood=E2=80=99s big night is on=
e of the last reasons so-called major studios still bother putting adult-sk=
ewing, prestige-chasing mid-budget movies in theaters.=C2=A0

