em>The Brutalist </em>added 780 theaters for a total of 1,118, and earned $=
2.8 million (+46 percent week over week), bringing its domestic total to $9=
=2E33 million.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;">More modest Oscar nomination
bumps included Paramount=E2=80=99s <em>September 5, </em>which was snubbed =
for best picture but earned $770,000 (+120 percent) in 394 theaters, while =
surprise best picture nominee <em>I=E2=80=99m Still Here </em>earned $240,0=
00 (+117 percent) in 17 theaters. <em>A Real Pain </em>added $76,000 (+27 p=
ercent) in 180 theaters, but it=E2=80=99s already available on V.O.D. and H=
ulu, diluting the nomination benefits. If studios are releasing a potential=
 mainstream contender like <em>Conclave</em> or last season=E2=80=99s
<em>The Holdovers </em>partially to capitalize on potential Oscar recogniti=
on, having those films on the same short theatrical-to-V.O.D. pipeline can =
be self-defeating.=C2=A0</p></div>
